{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"732d35d7-482d-43a6-a97d-a3a8b7a6cb6e","content":"Since there's no existing repo to reference, here's general guidance on evaluating MCP tool usage:\n\n## Evaluation Format (`evaluation.yml`)\n\nA standard evaluation file uses YAML with a list of test cases, each containing:\n\n```yaml\nevaluations:\n  - name: \"find_product_by_name\"\n    prompt: \"What is the price of the 'UltraWidget Pro'?\"\n    expected_tool_calls:\n      - tool: \"search_products\"\n        arguments:\n          name: \"UltraWidget Pro\"\n    expected_response_contains:\n      - \"$49.99\"\n\n  - name: \"filter_by_category\"\n    prompt: \"List all products in the 'Electronics' category under $100.\"\n    expected_tool_calls:\n      - tool: \"search_products\"\n        arguments:\n          category: \"Electronics\"\n          max_price: 100\n    expected_response_contains:\n      - \"UltraWidget Pro\"\n```\n\n## What Makes a Good Evaluation Question\n\n1. **Single-tool basics** — Does the LLM pick the right tool and pass correct arguments? (*\"What's the price of X?\"*)\n2. **Multi-tool chaining** — Can it compose tools? (*\"Compare the cheapest item in Electronics vs. Home.\"*)\n3. **Ambiguity handling** — Does it ask for clarification or make reasonable choices? (*\"Find the best widget.\"*)\n4. **Edge cases** — How does it handle no results, invalid input, or missing fields?\n5. **Argument mapping** — Does it correctly translate natural language filters into structured parameters (dates, ranges, enums)?\n\n**Tips:** Each question should test one clear behavior, have a deterministic expected outcome, and cover both the tool call shape and the natural-language response.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e38fdf5c-462c-460d-b72f-edb563264cc5","outputTokens":415,"requestId":"7012:8D0D7:60EF4DB:6C30A64:69EC1094"},"id":"0fbb0784-c9b4-4efe-bd82-04882a5ab0b0","timestamp":"2026-04-25T00:53:50.367Z","parentId":"e2986b93-568e-43ad-ac90-f3e55a4c2275"}
